Madness

Target IP: 10.10.5.10

Will you be consumed by Madness?

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The default webpage is displayed for this HTTP application. There is an interesting HTML comment inside the HTML page. Does the comment apply to the image?


However, the image is corrupt. Using an online website, I managed to fix the image. This image contains a text pointing to a hidden directory /th1s_1s_h1dd3n.


Browsing to /th1s_1s_h1dd3n displays the webpage above.


This page contains the source-code above. According to the HTML comment above, apparently the secret key is between 0-99. I will need to fuzz for the secret key using the parameter as secret.

nums = open("numbers.txt", "w")
for i in range(0, 100):
    nums.write(str(i))
    nums.write("\n")
nums.close()
nums = open("numbers.txt", "w")
for i in range(0, 100):
    nums.write(str(i))
    nums.write("\n")
nums.close()

I created the Python script above to output the numbers 0-99 in a text file called numbers.txt. Then using ffuf, I managed to fuzz the secret key.


Using the command ffuf -w numbers.txt -u http://10.10.5.10/th1s_1s_h1dd3n?secret=FUZZ, I found the secret key is 73. The password y2RPJ4QaPF!B is shown above. But what is the username?


Using steghide, I managed to obtain the hidden text file hidden.txt inside the thm.jpg file. This file mentions the username wbxre. However, using wbxre:y2RPJ4QaPF!B did not work against the SSH. Using multiple ciphers, I managed to decode the username to joker using ROT13. However, this did not work either.


I tested the different images in the room and got a hit. One of the image has the hidden data password.txt. The content of this file is shown above.

Exploitation


Using the credential joker:*axA&GF8dP, I managed to gain access to the target machine. Now I have a foothold.

Privilege Escalation


Running find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows the entry /bin/screen-4.5.0 which is vulnerable to local privilege escalation.


I obtained the code of the exploit for Screen 4.5.0. I browsed to /tmp and used vim to create the exploit as exp.sh. Then I executed it.


After running the exploit, I gained a root shell. Now I have root access.
